"v.动怜悯心；减弱 【英】 v. 动怜悯心(to become less severe, harsh, or strict)；减弱(soften, mollify) 【记】 re(重新)+lent(=bent 弯曲)→弯曲下来→变 温和 【例】 In the morning, the storm relented a little. 无 【记】re 再 + lend 过去时，又借给别人钱，真是慈悲 relent (v.)  late 14c., ""to melt, soften, dissolve,"" from re- + Latin lentus ""slow, viscous, supple"" (see lithe), perhaps on model of Old French rallentir. Sense of ""become less harsh or cruel"" first recorded 1520s. The notion probably is of a hard heart melting with pity. Related: Relented; relenting."
